metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #56
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Ari's Thread #123
metadata.description:
I side with the idea that we made this reality so weird merely to satisfy our -psychotic- need to overcomplicate things. Not you, of course.

That's why I believe that our choices don't "create our own path" but a maze for others to (try to) solve.
This God or that One or none, the old songs or the new ones, rooting for or against…
The deepest we meet into each other's maze, the more choices we share. Reciprocally, when we lack the interest to explore even a couple of turns, we're but a first impression to each other.

This work examines those ideas by continually presenting options to N individuals and then tracking their choices, which in turn generates different outputs at different depths.

To access them:
- press "S" for story mode, the sequence of choices
  - then, press "1" through "5" to change the speed
- press "L" for landscape, the first impression
- press "D" to see the details and view the mazes (may take a while)

metadata.name: Impressions of Order #169
metadata.description:
‘Impressions of Order’ is a collection of 300 generative compositions. 

Inspired by 90s ROM cartridges, server farms and future cityscapes this project explores perception and documentation of ‘order’ within complex systems. 

--------------------------------------------------------

This artwork is best enjoyed in high-resolution so that the subtle layering, colour shifts, variation in hard and soft edges, faint impressions of construction, and the various low-probability glitchy events can be fully appreciated. 

By default, the artwork will load in 2K resolution (1400 x 2000 px). It is recommended that you view the work in 4K or 6K to appreciate the finer details. 

The keyboard buttons: “2”, “4”, and “6” can be pressed to change the resolution to 2K, 4K and 6K resolution accordingly. 

To download an image at its current resolution, press the keyboard button “S”.

--------------------------------------------------------

Artwork created with p5.js

@nbswwit
Sept 2022

metadata.name: Natt #97
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press “space” to pause the animation and “s” to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add “?pd=x” (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press “s” to save. Note, for higher values of “x” rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size. 


Generative artwork by Tengil, 2022.

For licenses see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt.

metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #85
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Tuesday #116
metadata.description: Maybe it's inspired by the marks left by coffee cups in my notebook. Maybe the doodles in that same notebook, often squares and circles, somehow influenced this work. Maybe the Bridget Riley book sitting on the shelf above gently whispered to me when I wasn't looking. Or maybe I just played with an idea and found it pleasing. The only thing I'm certain of – it was definitely a Tuesday.

metadata.name: Chaos Culture #286
metadata.description:
"Chaos Culture" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

《西遊記》第一回:「混沌未分天地亂，茫茫渺渺無人見。」

Chaos Culture is the final chapter of this series. There is a legend in the East that before Pan Gu opened up the sky and created the earth, the world was a chaotic place, and no one knew its appearance. And I have always been fascinated by this mythical story since he was a child.

These three works have a father-son relationship, Research > Memory > Culture, with each work re-growing through the remnants of the previous work, depending on its image. From the beginning of the creative coding, I like the concept of recursion the most. Here I experiment with my central thinking through this iterative relationship so that the work is not only the shadow of the artist but also the pulling force of repetition.

"混沌" Chaos in Eastern culture represents the initial state of things. This state is consistent with what we believe in generative art: Anything can happen if different forces are applied. Letting chaos grow out of order and then destroying it, the iterative process, is like my usual dialogue with myself, and maybe it's all just a diary.

Through these three series of works, whether I can eventually find everything in my childhood fantasy, I am not sure yet. The only thing I can be sure of is that I will continue to explore.

- Click the mouse to save an artwork.
- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.

Artist: Aluan Wang (ileivoivm).
Made with p5js and glsl.
